    <section class="demos-intro" data-section-key="intro">
      <h1>IT Care &amp; Infrastructure</h1>
      <p class="lead">For anyone without their own IT department, from solo offices, practices and law firms up to mid-sized companies. I make sure your systems run, stay backed up, and can be recovered when it matters. None of this is theory: it's what I do in my own operation every day, 35+ virtual machines on my own Proxmox cluster, behind a multi-tier segmented network, with encrypted, restore-tested backups.</p>
    </section>

    <section data-section-key="leistungen">
      <h2>What I actually do</h2>
      <div class="fields">
        <article class="field">
          <h3>Backups that work when it counts</h3>
          <p>A backup that has never been restored is a promise, not protection. I set up encrypted backups, store them off-site and <strong>test the restore regularly</strong>, documented, so it's clear how it works in an emergency. You don't get a folder full of jargon, you get the certainty that the backup actually holds.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="field">
          <h3>Hardening and keeping servers current</h3>
          <p>Protection against attacks, automatic updates, clean permissions on the least-privilege principle, all documented and traceable. I work aligned with the German BSI baseline-protection methodology, so security isn't a one-off project but a maintained state.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="field">
          <h3>Databases that just run</h3>
          <p>Setup, hardening and maintenance of your PostgreSQL databases: with tested backups, applied updates and performance tuning when things get tight. Databases are my daily bread, I run multi-tenant systems with row-level security myself.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="field">
          <h3>Multiple servers on one machine (virtualization)</h3>
          <p>With Proxmox I split one physical server cleanly into separate virtual servers: that saves hardware and power, new servers are ready in minutes instead of days, and snapshots allow a fast return to the last good state. <strong>Moving off VMware?</strong> I get you out of the license costs and migrate you to Proxmox.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="field">
          <h3>High availability on request</h3>
          <p>Where an outage really hurts, systems run redundantly, so a single machine failing doesn't stop your business. Not cluster overkill for everyone, but the redundancy that fits your risk.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="field">
          <h3>Secure networks &amp; remote work</h3>
          <p>Devices cleanly separated into segments (VLANs), a firewall rule set on the principle "each segment only sees what it needs", and encrypted VPN access for safe work on the road. So nobody reaches anywhere they have no business being.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

